{"id":"0806.3309","submitter":"Shuichi Murakami","authors":"Shuichi Murakami, Shun-ichi Kuga","title":"Universal phase diagrams for the quantum spin Hall systems","comments":"10 pages, 8 figures, minor changes, to be published in Phys. Rev. B","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 78, 165313 (2008)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.78.165313","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We describe how the three-dimensional quantum spin Hall phase arises from the\ninsulator phase by changing an external parameter. In 3D systems without\ninversion symmetry, a gapless phase should appear between the two phases with a\nbulk gap. The gapless points are monopoles and antimonopoles (in k space),\nwhose topological nature is the source of this gapless phase. In general, when\nthe external parameter is changed from the ordinary insulator phase, two\nmonopole-antimonopole pairs are created and the system becomes gapless. The\ngap-closing points (monopoles and antimonopoles) then move in the k space as\nthe parameter is changed further. They eventually annihilate in pairs, with\nchanging partners from the pair creations, and the system opens a gap again,\nentering into the quantum spin Hall phase.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Jun 2008 03:06:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 8 Oct 2008 08:36:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-10-14"}
